TEXT.0: A 7-track ISIS 2 analog telemetry tape from Ottawa (#561) has been

TEXT.1: digitized using the GSFC facilities of the Data Evaluation Laboratory

TEXT.2: (DEL) within the Mission Operations and Data Systems Directorate (Code

TEXT.3: 500) at Goddard.  The digitization was performed using an A/D

TEXT.4: converter board and software device driver compatible with the OS/2

TEXT.5: operating system used by the 486-based Programmable Telemetry

TEXT.6: Processor (PTP) associated software has been installed on their PTP

TEXT.7: and de-bugged so that we now have a working system for making digital

TEXT.8: ISIS ionograms directly from the telemetry tapes.  Earlier, we

TEXT.9: successfully digitized the PCM and NASA 36 bit time-code data from

TEXT.10: this same tape. The ionograms were digitized at the rate of 40,000

TEXT.11: 16-bit samples/sec. This sample rate is higher than the Nyquist

TEXT.12: frequency of 30 kHz appropriate for the post-detection ISIS 2

TEXT.13: sounder-receiver video output which extends from DC to 15 kHz (see p.

TEXT.14: 50 of the 1971 ISIS 2 report by Daniels).  The sample frequency of 40

TEXT.15: kHz provides a measurement every 25 microseconds corresponding to an

TEXT.16: apparent range (ct/2) interval of 3.747 km.  With the ISIS 2 prf of 45

TEXT.18: between each of the approximately 1015 sounder pulses per ionogram

TEXT.21: sounder-receiver video data. Adding header information, and the pcm

TEXT.22: data containing data from the other instruments, yields about 2 MBytes

TEXT.23: of data for the 22.5 s period corresponding to one ionogram. Two steps

TEXT.24: were taken in order to reduce this large volume of nearly 2

TEXT.25: MBytes/ionogram.  First, every four 25 microsecond samples following

TEXT.26: the sounder pulse were averaged.  Second, the 16 bit samples were

TEXT.27: reduced to 8 bit samples.  The first step decreased the apparent-range

TEXT.28: resolution to 15 km, but yielded high-quality ionograms because of the

TEXT.29: improved S/N due to the averaging.
